   <mods:abstract>Is at present ill and unable to peruse the necessary papers in order to
            give a concise statement. However he will try to give Pickering some of the information
            he requested. Includes an extract from instructions of Congress to their Peace
            Commissioners telling them to confide all subjects to the ministers of France and to
            undertake nothing without their concurrence. Shows his disapproval of this policy in a
            letter to the President of Congress, 20 Sept. 1781, and extracts from two letters to
            Livingston, 18 Sept. and 13 Oct., 1782. Also includes an extract from a conference with
            Floridablanca on 23 Sept. 1780, revealing that the King of Spain had not known of the
            treaty between France and America, and that his resentment had nearly caused a rupture
            between the two Courts.</mods:abstract>
